courses.learning_outcomes:
By the end of the course, participants will be able to:

1. understand the aims and objectives of modules 5 and 6 in the Liberal Studies curriculum;
2. understand the scientific and technological principles and social implications of “Public Health and Technology” and “Energy and the Environment”;
3. design appropriate instructional strategies for facilitating pupils’ effective learning in modules 5 and 6;
4. plan lessons in modules 5 and 6 with issue enquiry approach

5. examine the issues inherent in the teaching and learning of public health and environmental issues in Liberal Studies.

By the end of the course, students will be able to:

1. understand the major concepts of Culture and Society;
2. identify the relevant pedagogical strategies in teaching the issues related to Hong Kong Today, Modern China and Globalization;
3. apply the appropriate concepts and pedagogical strategies to design the teaching plan with issue enquiry approach.

Upon completion of this course, students are expected to be able to:

1. explain the nature of Liberal Studies as an integrated curriculum and its realization in school context;
2. foster the relevant pedagogical competency, in particular issue enquiry approach, and underlying attitudes for teaching Liberal Studies;
3. analyse perennial issues using the foundational knowledge of liberal studies in correspondence with the three areas of studies in senior secondary Liberal Studies curriculum; and

4. investigate current issues similar issues in related to Liberal Studies lessons curriculum with multiple perspectives.

Upon completion of the course, students should be able to:

1. understand the nature of Liberal Studies & its theoretical and pedagogical foundations and discern interpretations of its genesis & its significance;
2. use methods of inquiry, including conceptual, factual, evaluative and critical inquiries in one's learning;
3. employ issue-based inquiry as the primary pedagogical approach to Liberal Studies when deploying issues related to Liberal Studies curriculum in Hong Kong secondary schools.

By the end of the course, students will be able to
1. understand how integrated curriculum in Hong Kong are shaped by pedagogical innovations such as issue-based learning, and how it is different from conventional subjects which have strong academic traditions;
2. understand the possible options for and problems of curriculum mapping in the implementation of Liberal Studies/Citizenship and Social Development in Hong Kong;
3. understand the need to bridge the gap between school-based curriculum in junior secondary school and Liberal Studies/Citizenship and Social Development in senior secondary school from the perspective of assessment for learning;
4. reflect on previous experience of designing individual teaching package and reach a deeper understanding of assessment criteria for effective classroom teaching

By the end of the course, students will be able to
1. develop active teaching strategies such as mind maps, concept maps, group discussion, active reading, active writing;
2. develop skills in lesson planning;
3. develop principles and teaching skills in microteaching;
4. perform and reflect on practical teaching.

By the end of the course, students will be able to
1. review classroom experience by using a case method which comprises four attributes: intention, chance, judgment and reflection;
2. revisit the nature of pedagogical content knowledge by using a narrative method which comprises four dimensions: practical experience, interpretation, reflection and transformation;
3. involve in case organization, case writing, case commentary and case conferences;
4. develop teacher knowledge through effective learning such as agency, reflection and collaboration.

By the end of the course, participants will be able to:
1. understand the stages of portfolio growth: an off-track portfolio, an emerging portfolio, an on-track portfolio and an outstanding portfolio;
2. review their own portfolio and become more aware of the stages of professional development;
3. develop critical thinking skills in content selection and lesson planning;
4. acquire skills in catering for individual differences and assessment for learning.
